        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I remember when @lewis6991 pointed out the performance difference caused by indexing methods, I did a quick benchmark showing about a 4x gap. However, the re-test I conducted yesterday showed that the resulting performance gap is small; see https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/38561#issuecomment-4326214346. I'm not entirely sure if I did something wrong.\r\n\r\nThe significance of keeping hash indexing is that we can provide more functionality for `pos`/`buf`. For example, an idea I had previously was to allow `range` to have a `data` field that can hold arbitrary data. Another example is that the current `buf` also doesn't seem suitable for indexing with numbers. \r\n\r\nWhen `pos` and `range` have fields other than `row` and `col`, it becomes quite strange to continue using numeric indexing (which is why I kept the `buf` indexing method even in this PR), because `buf` would be `pos[3]` in a `pos` but `range[5]` in a `range`. If we were to add even more fields to `range` using numeric indexing, we would encounter this same issue.",
            "created_at": "2026-04-27T16:56:06Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/39447#issuecomment-4328883553",
            "id": 4328883553,
            "issue_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/neovim/neovim/issues/39447",
            "node_id": "IC_kwDOAPphoM8AAAABAgWFYQ",
            "performed_via_github_app": null,
            "reactions": {
